Sciurus carolinensis Gmelin, 1788
occurrenceRemarks: This is an Eastern Gray Squirrel under Sciurus carolinensis. This organism is sporting a grayish tan coat followed by a pale white underbelly, and white strips along the sides of the tail. This squirrel is a tetrapod looking to be approximately .60 kg. The color of its fur is a clear indication of the organism along with its location helping to narrow the options. This organism is clearly a rodent part of the Sciurus genus, and the coat color provides the identification of Sciurus carolinensis. According to https://myfwc.com/wildlifehabitats/profiles/mammals/land/squirrels/ I was able to identify the species. The habitat for the animal is woodland and urban areas, the geographical distribution would be if one drew a line down the center of the USA and then proceeded to shade everything on the right side, bounded also including some of Canada.

occurrenceRemarks: The observation of the Eastern Gray Squirrel was taken during warm and cloudy weather. The Eastern Gray Squirrel in the observation is around 12 inches tall and has a light grayish brown coat, grayish colored underside, grayish white rings around its eyes, and a tail that is large, lightweight, furry, and gray.These physical characteristics can be compared to the typical traits found in Eastern Gray Squirrels such as the dorsal surface that ranges from dark to pale grey, ears that are white or gray, underparts that are grey, and a tail that ranges from white to pale grey. The Eastern Gray Squirrel was observed in the trees on the University of South Florida's Campus in front of the Marshall Student Center. The Eastern Gray Squirrel was observed to naturally inhabit the trees on USF's Campus as they can be found to live all around the Eastern United States in temperate forest-like environments. The Eastern Gray Squirrel is also distributed in the MidWestern United States and Eastern Canada. They are under Kingdom Animalia and Phylum chordata as they have a central nervous system made of the brain and vertebral column. Reference: https://animaldiversity.org/accounts/Sciurus_carolinensis/

occurrenceRemarks: This organism has a bushy tail, a white underside, and is primarily black in color with some brown furs. They use their big tails for balance as they climb trees. Most eastern gray squirrels are around 50 cm long including their tail. This specific organism was found on the campus of the University of South Florida on the Martin Luther King Lawn. This animal is found mostly in woodlands in eastern North America. Based on the location of the organism and the color of the coat, the bushy tail, and its moderate size, it can be classified as the Genus Sciurus. This organism belongs to the Kingdom Animalia, Phylum Chordata, Class Mammalia, Order Rodentia, Family Sciuridae, Genus Sciurus. Reference: http://www.animalspot.net/eastern-gray-squirrel.html

verbatimLocality: University of South Florida, Tampa, FL, US
name: Sciurus carolinensis Gmelin, 1788
occurrenceRemarks: This squirrel was found on campus enjoying his breakfast which seems to be a French fry. This squirrel seemed to be a little in the heavier side and has a nice bushy tail, white fur on the belly and a mixture of black and tanned fur on the rest in the body. The habitat where organism was found consisted of 54 degree temperature and a sunny, nearly cloudless sky with a slight wind. The squirrel can be found on every continent except Australia and Antarctica according to BBC. There is also both ground squirrels and tree squirrels although Im not quite sure which this one is. A defining characteristic for the squirrels family Sciuridae is that the back legs are longer than the front ones all with four or five toes (Wikipedia).

name: Sciurus carolinensis Gmelin, 1788
occurrenceRemarks: Squirrel has gray-brown coloration on body and head, a white underbelly and bushy tail bordered with white hairs, characteristic of this species. Spotted on the stairs of the Allen Building at USF. The Eastern Gray Squirrel are found in eastern United States, from just west of Mississippi River and north to Canada. Habitat: diverse and large woodlands, especially with high densities of oak walnut trees (which provide enough food for winter storage). They are also found in urban and suburban areas. Weather Condition: 54 degrees Fahrenheit, cloudy skies, slightly windy. Reference: https://myfwc.com/wildlifehabitats/profiles/mammals/land/squirrels/

verbatimLocality: Interdisciplinary Science Teaching and Research Facility, USF Cherry Dr, Tampa, FL 33620, USA
name: Sciurus carolinensis Gmelin, 1788
occurrenceRemarks: This eastern gray squirrel was spotted on a palm tree outside of the Interdisciplinary Science building on the USF campus. It exhibited defensive behavior upon discovery, as a cat was watching it from the base of the tree. The squirrel had the classic fluffy tail of its species and had a brown-gray coat with a white underbelly. The eastern gray squirrel is a very common mammal that is distributed throughout the entire eastern United States up to Canada, as stated in the source below: https://animaldiversity.org/accounts/Sciurus_carolinensis/ The squirrels specifically found on the USF campus enjoy a fairly unthreatened life where they survive off of the abundance of acorns and thrown-away food from college students when the opportunity arises.
